Implement `marketplace-cache.ts` which manages `~/.dork/cache/marketplace/` with TTL semantics and content-addressable storage for cloned packages.

## File

`apps/server/src/services/marketplace/marketplace-cache.ts`

## Layout (verbatim from spec)

```
~/.dork/cache/marketplace/
├── marketplaces/
│   └── dorkos-community/
│       ├── marketplace.json           # Last fetched (1h TTL)
│       └── .last-fetched               # Timestamp
└── packages/
    ├── code-review-suite@a3f4b21/      # Content-addressable by commit SHA
    │   └── (cloned package)
    └── code-review-suite@b8c1d99/
        └── (cloned package)
```

## TTL strategy (verbatim from spec)

- `marketplace.json`: 1 hour. After expiry, refetch in background, serve stale on failure.
- Cloned packages: Never expire. Garbage-collected only on explicit `dorkos cache prune`.

## Public API

```typescript
export interface CachedMarketplace {
  json: MarketplaceJson;
  fetchedAt: Date;
  stale: boolean;
}

export interface CachedPackage {
  packageName: string;
  commitSha: string;
  path: string;
  cachedAt: Date;
}

export class MarketplaceCache {
  constructor(
    private readonly dorkHome: string,
    private readonly ttlMs: number = 60 * 60 * 1000 // 1h
  ) {}

  /** Read cached marketplace.json. Returns { stale: true } if past TTL. Returns null if absent. */
  async readMarketplace(marketplaceName: string): Promise<CachedMarketplace | null>;

  /** Write marketplace.json to cache and stamp .last-fetched. */
  async writeMarketplace(marketplaceName: string, json: MarketplaceJson): Promise<void>;

  /** Get a cached package by name + commit SHA. Returns null if absent. */
  async getPackage(packageName: string, commitSha: string): Promise<CachedPackage | null>;

  /** Reserve a package directory in the cache and return its path. Caller writes contents. */
  async putPackage(packageName: string, commitSha: string): Promise<string>;

  /** List every cached package across all names + SHAs. */
  async listPackages(): Promise<CachedPackage[]>;

  /** Garbage-collect: remove every package SHA except the most recent N per name. */
  async prune(opts?: { keepLastN?: number }): Promise<{ removed: CachedPackage[] }>;

  /** Wipe the entire cache directory. */
  async clear(): Promise<void>;

  /** Compute the cache root path. */
  get cacheRoot(): string;
}
```

## Implementation notes

- Use `${dorkHome}/cache/marketplace/marketplaces/${name}/` and `${dorkHome}/cache/marketplace/packages/${name}@${sha}/`.
- `MarketplaceJson` type comes from `@dorkos/marketplace` (foundation spec).
- Validate cached JSON via `parseMarketplaceJson` from `@dorkos/marketplace` on read; treat parse failure as cache miss.
- `prune` defaults to `keepLastN: 1` (keeps the latest version of each package).
- Compute `stale` as `Date.now() - fetchedAt.getTime() > ttlMs`.

## Tests

Create `apps/server/src/services/marketplace/__tests__/marketplace-cache.test.ts`:

- `readMarketplace` returns null when absent.
- `writeMarketplace` then `readMarketplace` round-trips with `stale: false`.
- After advancing time past TTL, `readMarketplace` returns `stale: true` but still returns the JSON.
- `getPackage` returns null when absent; returns the path when present.
- `putPackage` creates the directory and returns its path.
- `prune({ keepLastN: 1 })` removes older SHAs, keeps newest per package name.
- `clear()` removes the entire `cache/marketplace/` tree.
- `listPackages()` enumerates all cached SHAs across all names.
- Use `vi.useFakeTimers()` to test TTL expiry.

## Acceptance criteria

- [ ] All methods implemented per signature above
- [ ] TTL logic correct (stale flag set, not erased)
- [ ] Atomic write of `.last-fetched` after `marketplace.json`
- [ ] Vitest tests pass including TTL expiry and prune scenarios
- [ ] Constructor takes `dorkHome: string`
- [ ] TSDoc on every public method

Implement `package-resolver.ts` which converts user input like `code-review-suite@dorkos-community`, `github:user/repo`, or `./local/path` into a concrete package source descriptor.

## File

`apps/server/src/services/marketplace/package-resolver.ts`

## Public API

```typescript
export type PackageSourceKind = 'marketplace' | 'git' | 'local';

export interface ResolvedPackageSource {
  kind: PackageSourceKind;
  /** Package name (post-`@` portion stripped) */
  packageName: string;
  /** Marketplace name when kind === 'marketplace' */
  marketplaceName?: string;
  /** Git URL when kind === 'git' or 'marketplace' (after marketplace lookup) */
  gitUrl?: string;
  /** Absolute local path when kind === 'local' */
  localPath?: string;
  /** Optional version pin (post-`#` or `@version` syntax — not required for v1) */
  version?: string;
}

export class PackageResolver {
  constructor(
    private readonly sourceManager: MarketplaceSourceManager,
    private readonly cache: MarketplaceCache
  ) {}

  /**
   * Resolve a user-supplied identifier into a concrete source.
   * Supports:
   *   - `name`                       → search all enabled marketplaces
   *   - `name@marketplaceName`       → look up in specific marketplace
   *   - `name@<git url>`             → direct git URL
   *   - `github:user/repo`           → git shorthand → https://github.com/user/repo
   *   - `./relative/path` or `/abs`  → local directory
   */
  async resolve(input: string): Promise<ResolvedPackageSource>;
}
```

## Resolution algorithm

1. **Local path** — if `input` starts with `./`, `../`, `/`, or matches a Windows drive letter (`C:\`), treat as `local`. Resolve to absolute path. Verify directory exists.
2. **Git shorthand** — if `input` matches `^github:([^/]+)/([^/]+)$`, expand to `https://github.com/$1/$2`. Kind = `git`. `packageName` = repo name.
3. **Explicit git URL after `@`** — if `input` is `name@<url>` and the right side parses as a URL (`new URL`), kind = `git`. `packageName` = left side.
4. **Explicit marketplace after `@`** — if `input` is `name@marketplaceName`, look up the marketplace via `sourceManager.get()`. If absent → throw `MarketplaceNotFoundError`. Read its `marketplace.json` (via `cache.readMarketplace`, fetching if absent — for v1 use a TODO and only handle the cached case; an actual fetch will be wired in 1.5). Find the entry by `name`. Kind = `marketplace`.
5. **Bare name** — search all enabled sources from `sourceManager.list()`, returning the first hit. If multiple hits, throw `AmbiguousPackageError` listing the marketplaces. If zero hits, throw `PackageNotFoundError`.

## Errors

Define and export typed errors:

```typescript
export class MarketplaceNotFoundError extends Error {}
export class PackageNotFoundError extends Error {}
export class AmbiguousPackageError extends Error {
  constructor(public readonly packageName: string, public readonly marketplaces: string[]) {
    super(`Package '${packageName}' exists in multiple marketplaces: ${marketplaces.join(', ')}`);
  }
}
```

## Tests

Create `apps/server/src/services/marketplace/__tests__/package-resolver.test.ts`:

- Resolves `./fixture-pkg` to a local source with absolute path.
- Resolves `github:user/repo` to `https://github.com/user/repo`.
- Resolves `pkg@https://github.com/x/y` to a git source with `packageName: 'pkg'`.
- Resolves `pkg@my-marketplace` against a mocked source manager + cache.
- Throws `AmbiguousPackageError` when bare name resolves in 2+ marketplaces.
- Throws `PackageNotFoundError` when bare name unresolvable.
- Throws `MarketplaceNotFoundError` when explicit marketplace doesn't exist.
- Mock `sourceManager` and `cache` with stub implementations.

## Acceptance criteria

- [ ] All 5 resolution paths implemented
- [ ] All three typed errors exported
- [ ] TSDoc on `resolve()` listing every supported input format
- [ ] Tests cover every branch including error cases

Add a thin wrapper around the existing `apps/server/src/services/core/template-downloader.ts` that fetches and caches marketplace package contents. This avoids any modification to template-downloader itself — it's consumed via its existing public API only (per spec acceptance criterion: `Zero changes to existing services beyond their public APIs`).

## File

`apps/server/src/services/marketplace/package-fetcher.ts`

## Public API

```typescript
export interface FetchPackageOptions {
  /** Package name (used for cache key) */
  packageName: string;
  /** Git URL to clone */
  gitUrl: string;
  /** Optional ref/branch (defaults to default branch) */
  ref?: string;
  /** Force refetch even if already cached */
  force?: boolean;
}

export interface FetchedPackage {
  /** Filesystem path of the cached package */
  path: string;
  /** Commit SHA the cache is keyed by */
  commitSha: string;
  /** Whether the result came from cache */
  fromCache: boolean;
}

export class PackageFetcher {
  constructor(
    private readonly cache: MarketplaceCache,
    private readonly templateDownloader: TemplateDownloader,
    private readonly logger: Logger
  ) {}

  /**
   * Fetch a package from a git URL. Caches by commit SHA so repeated fetches
   * for the same SHA are no-ops.
   *
   * Algorithm:
   *   1. Resolve commit SHA from gitUrl + ref via `git ls-remote`.
   *   2. Check cache.getPackage(packageName, sha). If present and !force, return.
   *   3. Otherwise, reserve a cache directory via cache.putPackage().
   *   4. Use templateDownloader to clone into the cache directory.
   *   5. Return the cached path + commit SHA.
   */
  async fetchFromGit(opts: FetchPackageOptions): Promise<FetchedPackage>;

  /**
   * Fetch and cache a marketplace.json from a marketplace source. Honors TTL.
   * On network failure with stale cache available, returns the stale copy with a warning logged.
   */
  async fetchMarketplaceJson(source: MarketplaceSource): Promise<MarketplaceJson>;
}
```

## Implementation notes

- **Resolving commit SHA without cloning**: spawn `git ls-remote <gitUrl> <ref|HEAD>` and parse the first column. If git binary unavailable or network down, fall back to a deterministic `tmp-${Date.now()}` SHA so the cache miss path always works (the actual clone may still fail later).
- The existing `template-downloader.ts` was designed for templates; reuse its public clone API. If its current API only supports template-shaped repos, add a new method `cloneRepository(gitUrl, destDir, ref?)` to template-downloader with no behavior change to existing code paths. **Read the file first and prefer the smallest possible addition.**
- For `fetchMarketplaceJson`, use `node:fetch` to GET `${gitUrl.replace(/\.git$/, '')}/raw/main/marketplace.json` (or similar — match spec 01's marketplace.json discovery convention). Parse via `parseMarketplaceJson` from `@dorkos/marketplace`. On success, write to cache; on failure, return stale cache or rethrow.
- Inject `Logger` from `@dorkos/shared/logger`.

## Tests

Create `apps/server/src/services/marketplace/__tests__/package-fetcher.test.ts`:

- Cache hit: when `cache.getPackage()` returns a path, no clone is invoked, `fromCache: true`.
- Cache miss: clone is invoked, result written to cache.
- `force: true` bypasses cache hit.
- `fetchMarketplaceJson` writes to cache and returns parsed JSON.
- `fetchMarketplaceJson` serves stale on network failure (mock fetch to reject).
- Mock `templateDownloader`, `cache`, and `fetch` (use `vi.stubGlobal('fetch', ...)`).

